reason.tex:
%text
The general equation of a circle that is
\underline\text{centered at the origin} is  $x^2+y^2=R^2$. 

And therefore, 

%
\begin{align}
4x^2 + 4y^2 &= 9 \implies x^2 + y^2 = \frac{9}{4} \\
\implies x^2+y^2 &= \underbrace{\left( \frac{3}{2}\right)^2}_{R^2}  \\
\implies R &= \frac{3}{2}\text{ units}
\end{align}

%text
In the range $x=-\sqrt{2}\rightarrow x=\sqrt{2}$, the 
\underline\text{circle lies above the parabola}. Hence, the
required area $R$ will be given by 
%
\begin{align}
R &= \int_{-\sqrt{2}}^\sqrt{2}\left( \sqrt{\frac{9}{4}-x^2} - \frac{x^2}{4}\right)\cdot dx
\end{align} 
%text

But the figure is \underline\text{symmetrical} around the 
y-axis. Hence, we can also say that,
%
\begin{align}
R &= \underbrace{2\cdot\left[ \int_0^\sqrt{2}\left( \sqrt{\frac{9}{4}-x^2} - \frac{x^2}{4}\right)\cdot dx\right]}
_{\text{due to symmetry}} 
\end{align}
